(24, 'PUBG Ban: PTA To Take Final Decision Today', 'The Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) has concluded hearing whether ban on online game PlayerUnknown’s Battlegrounds (PUBG) will be extended or removed.\r\n\r\nThe authority, earlier issued a hearing notice to all respondents. It had allowed them to join the meeting via video link because of the ongoing coronavirus situation.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, #PTALiftBanOnPUBG is trending on Twitter as social media users demand to lift PUBG ban from Pakistan.', 'The Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) has concluded hearing whether ban on online game PlayerUnknown’s Battlegrounds (PUBG) will be extended or removed.\r\n\r\nThe authority, earlier issued a hearing notice to all respondents. It had allowed them to join the meeting via video link because of the ongoing coronavirus situation.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, #PTALiftBanOnPUBG is trending on Twitter as social media users demand to lift PUBG ban from Pakistan.\r\n\r\nA temporary ban was imposed on the battle royale game on July 1. The authority said it received ‘numerous complaints against PUBG wherein it is stated that the game is addictive, wastage of time and poses a serious negative impact on the physical and psychological health of children.’\r\n\r\nPetitions were filed against the ban in the Sindh High Court (SHC) and the Islamabad High Court (IHC).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOn July 6, the IHC sent the petition against the suspension of online game PUBG to the PTA.\r\n\r\nPUBG, which has been developed by a South Korean company, is a 2017 survival game in which players drop onto an island to battle it out against others.\r\n\r\nThe multiplayer game allows players from all over the world to compete against each other or in teams.\r\n\r\nPlayers attack and kill each other in the game and the more you win, the higher you rank. It has garnered 34.2 million downloads worldwide so far.\r\n\r\nHowever, on June 20, a 20-year-old took his own life in Saddar Bazaar in North Cantonment. The police said that his parents had stopped him from playing the game.\r\n\r\nThree days later, another suicide reported in Hanjarwal. Operations DIG Ashfaq Ahmed Khan said that they found the young man’s cell phone in the room and the PUBG app was running on it.', 'pubg-ban-pta-to-take-final-decision-today', 8, 1, 'post_main24.jpg', 'post_thumb24.jpg', 'post_list24.jpg', 2, 0, 1, 0, '2020-07-11 05:13:26', '2020-07-11 09:09:51'),
(25, 'Pakistani Mangoes On Their Way To Japan', 'Now Japan can also have the taste of Pakistani mangoes this year as the country has allowed Pakistan to export the king of fruits.\r\n\r\nThe export of mangoes was allowed under temporary arrangements due to the unavailability of Japanese inspectors in Pakistan amid the coronavirus pandemic.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Japanese embassy in Pakistan, last year 120 tons of mangoes were exported from Pakistan to Japan, which is a record and shows how Pakistani mangoes are adapted in Japanese markets.', 'Now Japan can also have the taste of Pakistani mangoes this year as the country has allowed Pakistan to export the king of fruits.\r\n\r\nThe export of mangoes was allowed under temporary arrangements due to the unavailability of Japanese inspectors in Pakistan amid the coronavirus pandemic.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Japanese embassy in Pakistan, last year 120 tons of mangoes were exported from Pakistan to Japan, which is a record and shows how Pakistani mangoes are adapted in Japanese markets.\r\n\r\nIn general, the export of Pakistani mangoes to Japan is subject to Japanese inspector approval. Nevertheless, Pakistani mangoes were allowed to be exported this year under temporary arrangements without Japanese inspectors’ permission.\r\n\r\nThe Japanese inspectors were unable to come to Pakistan because of coronavirus pandemic.', 'pakistani-mangoes-on-their-way-to-japan', 8, 1, 'post_main25.jpg', 'post_thumb25.jpg', 'post_list25.jpg', 0, 0, 1, 0, '2020-07-11 05:15:01', '2020-07-11 05:15:01'),
(26, 'PIA Reduces Fares For Domestic Travelling', 'Pakistan International Airlines (PIA) has made a historic reduction in domestic fares.\r\n\r\nAccording to Spokesperson of PIA, the one way fare from Karachi to Islamabad has been fixed to Rs. 9572.\r\n\r\nSpokesperson said that similarly the one-way fare between Karachi and Lahore has also fixed to Rs 9572. Passengers will be allowed to hand carry seven kilograms of luggage with them when traveling domestically.\r\n\r\nA spokesman for the national airline said the new fares issued for domestic travel would take effect immediately.', 'Pakistan International Airlines (PIA) has made a historic reduction in domestic fares.\r\n\r\nAccording to Spokesperson of PIA, the one way fare from Karachi to Islamabad has been fixed to Rs. 9572.\r\n\r\nSpokesperson said that similarly the one-way fare between Karachi and Lahore has also fixed to Rs 9572. Passengers will be allowed to hand carry seven kilograms of luggage with them when traveling domestically.\r\n\r\nA spokesman for the national airline said the new fares issued for domestic travel would take effect immediately.\r\n\r\nThe national flag carrier had announced a reduction in fares for all domestic flights a week ago.\r\n\r\nThe PIA spokesman said that the one-way fare for Karachi, Lahore, Islamabad and other cities has been fixed to Rs 12,000.\r\n\r\nFurthermore the spokesperson had said that PIA has reduced fares for the convenience of passengers which will be applicable from today.', 'pia-reduces-fares-for-domestic-travelling', 8, 1, 'post_main26.jpg', 'post_thumb26.jpg', 'post_list26.jpg', 0, 0, 1, 0, '2020-07-11 05:15:46', '2020-07-11 05:15:46'),
(27, 'Pakistan Faces Petrol Crisis Due To Incumbent PTI Government: Shahid Khaqan', 'Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N) senior leader Shahid Khaqan Abbasi has said that the petroleum crisis in the country is due to incumbent government of Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI).\r\n\r\nAddressing a press conference, Khaqan Abbasi claimed that the Imran-led has taken advantage from the petrol crisis.\r\n\r\nPrime Minister Imran Khan should leave the government as he has failed to run the country in smooth way, he proposed.', 'Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N) senior leader Shahid Khaqan Abbasi has said that the petroleum crisis in the country is due to incumbent government of Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI).\r\n\r\nAddressing a press conference, Khaqan Abbasi claimed that the Imran-led has taken advantage from the petrol crisis.\r\n\r\nPrime Minister Imran Khan should leave the government as he has failed to run the country in smooth way, he proposed.\r\n\r\nThe PML-N leader further said that those who worked for the development of the country have been declared culprits in fake corruption cases.\r\n\r\nPML-N had ensured electricity at cheap rates in its tenure to provide relief to the nation, he added.\r\n\r\nThe former PM has also urged everyone to work together for Pakistan’s best interest.\r\n\r\nEarlier, Shahid Khaqan Abbasi said that PM Imran and his government has lost all faith and trust of its allies.', 'pakistan-faces-petrol-crisis-due-to-incumbent-pti-government-shahid-khaqan', 8, 1, 'post_main27.jpg', 'post_thumb27.jpg', 'post_list27.jpg', 0, 0, 1, 0, '2020-07-11 05:16:24', '2020-07-11 05:16:25');
